titleproper.value:
Guide to the E. L. Doctorow Papers 
                    <lb/>
                    <date>1931-2015 </date>
                    <num>MSS 056</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Processed by Tania Friedel, May - August 2001, and Matt Moore, September 2001 - January 2003.

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2016-05-09T12:26-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
E. L. Doctorow was an American novelist whose work includes the novels 
                <title render="italic">Welcome to Hard Times</title>, 
                <title render="italic">Big As Life</title>, 
                <title render="italic">The Book of Daniel</title>, 
                <title render="italic">Ragtime</title>, 
                <title render="italic">Loon Lake</title>, 
                <title render="italic">World's Fair</title>, 
                <title render="italic">Billy Bathgate</title>, 
                <title render="italic">The Waterworks</title>, and 
                <title render="italic">City of God</title>; a play, 
                <title render="italic">Drinks Before Dinner</title>; a collection of short fiction, 
                <title render="italic">Lives of the Poets</title>, and a collection of non-fiction, 
                <title render="italic">Jack London, Hemingway, and the Constitution</title>. He won numerous awards, including The National Book Critics Circle Award, the National Book Award, the Award in Arts and Letters from the American Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters, and the P.E.N./Faulkner Award, and held the Glucksman Chair in American Letters at New York University. The collection comprises correspondence, manuscripts, press, subject file, photographs, and other documents related to his writing and personal life.

p.value: Audiovisual materials have not been preserved and may not be available to researchers.

Published citations should take the following form:
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date (if known); The E. L. Doctorow Papers; MSS #56; box number; folder number;

                        <lb/> </addressline>
                    <addressline>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library
                        <lb/> </addressline>
                    <addressline>70 Washington Square South
                        <lb/> </addressline>
                    <addressline>New York, NY 10012</addressline>
                </address>

Sources: 
                <list>
                    <item>1 Yardley, Jonathan, "Mr. Ragtime," The Miami Herald, 21 December 1975.</item>
                    <item>2 Wutz, Michael, "An Interview with E.L. Doctorow," Weber Studies 11 (Winter, 1994).</item>
                    <item>3 Baker, John F., "PW Interviews: E.L. Doctorow," Publisher's Weekly 207 (30 June 1975).</item>
                    <item>4 Weber, Bruce, “E.L. Doctorow Dies at 84; Literary Time Traveler Stirred Past Into Fiction,” New York Times 21 July 2015: Online.</item>
                </list>
